The [`using enum type;`](command:_github.copilot.openSymbolFromReferences?%5B%7B%22%24mid%22%3A1%2C%22external%22%3A%22file%3A%2F%2F%2Fc%253A%2Fmsys64%2Fucrt64%2Finclude%2Fc%252B%252B%2F13.2.0%2Farray%22%2C%22path%22%3A%22%2Fc%3A%2Fmsys64%2Fucrt64%2Finclude%2Fc%2B%2B%2F13.2.0%2Farray%22%2C%22scheme%22%3A%22file%22%7D%2C%7B%22line%22%3A468%2C%22character%22%3A12%7D%5D "../../../msys64/ucrt64/include/c++/13.2.0/array") statement in C++ is used to introduce the enumerators of the enumeration [`type`](command:_github.copilot.openSymbolFromReferences?%5B%7B%22%24mid%22%3A1%2C%22external%22%3A%22file%3A%2F%2F%2Fc%253A%2Fmsys64%2Fucrt64%2Finclude%2Fc%252B%252B%2F13.2.0%2Farray%22%2C%22path%22%3A%22%2Fc%3A%2Fmsys64%2Fucrt64%2Finclude%2Fc%2B%2B%2F13.2.0%2Farray%22%2C%22scheme%22%3A%22file%22%7D%2C%7B%22line%22%3A468%2C%22character%22%3A12%7D%5D "../../../msys64/ucrt64/include/c++/13.2.0/array") into the enclosing scope. This is a feature introduced in C++20 known as "Enum Unscoped". 

This means that you can use the enumerators directly without having to prefix them with the enum type. 

For example, consider the following enum:

```cpp
enum class Color {
    Red,
    Green,
    Blue
};
```

Normally, to use the enumerators, you would have to prefix them with the enum type, like so: `Color::Red`, `Color::Green`, `Color::Blue`. 

But if you use the `using enum` statement, you can use the enumerators directly:

```cpp
using enum Color;

// Now you can use the enumerators directly
Color c = Red;
```

In your code, [`using enum type;`](command:_github.copilot.openSymbolFromReferences?%5B%7B%22%24mid%22%3A1%2C%22external%22%3A%22file%3A%2F%2F%2Fc%253A%2Fmsys64%2Fucrt64%2Finclude%2Fc%252B%252B%2F13.2.0%2Farray%22%2C%22path%22%3A%22%2Fc%3A%2Fmsys64%2Fucrt64%2Finclude%2Fc%2B%2B%2F13.2.0%2Farray%22%2C%22scheme%22%3A%22file%22%7D%2C%7B%22line%22%3A468%2C%22character%22%3A12%7D%5D "../../../msys64/ucrt64/include/c++/13.2.0/array") is used inside the `to_cstring` function to allow the `switch` statement to use the enumerators of [`type`](command:_github.copilot.openSymbolFromReferences?%5B%7B%22%24mid%22%3A1%2C%22external%22%3A%22file%3A%2F%2F%2Fc%253A%2Fmsys64%2Fucrt64%2Finclude%2Fc%252B%252B%2F13.2.0%2Farray%22%2C%22path%22%3A%22%2Fc%3A%2Fmsys64%2Fucrt64%2Finclude%2Fc%2B%2B%2F13.2.0%2Farray%22%2C%22scheme%22%3A%22file%22%7D%2C%7B%22line%22%3A468%2C%22character%22%3A12%7D%5D "../../../msys64/ucrt64/include/c++/13.2.0/array") directly in the `case` statements.

