Yes, the Configurable Fault Status Register (CFSR) is one of the fault status registers in ARM Cortex-M processors that can provide information about the cause of a HardFault. 

The CFSR is divided into three parts: the Memory Management Fault Status Register (MMFSR), the Bus Fault Status Register (BFSR), and the Usage Fault Status Register (UFSR). Each of these registers can provide specific information about the type of fault that occurred.

To use the CFSR in your HardFault handler, you would need to read its value and then check the specific bits that correspond to the different types of faults. Here's an example of how you could modify the HardFault handler to do this:

```c
#include "core_cm4.h" // Include CMSIS header for Cortex-M4

void HardFault_Handler(void)
{
    // Read the CFSR
    uint32_t cfsr = SCB->CFSR;

    // Check for memory management fault
    if ((cfsr & SCB_CFSR_MEMFAULTSR_Msk) != 0) {
        // Handle memory management fault
    }

    // Check for bus fault
    if ((cfsr & SCB_CFSR_BUSFAULTSR_Msk) != 0) {
        // Handle bus fault
    }

    // Check for usage fault
    if ((cfsr & SCB_CFSR_USGFAULTSR_Msk) != 0) {
        // Handle usage fault
    }

    while(1);
}
```

This code reads the value of the CFSR and then checks the bits that correspond to the different types of faults. If a bit is set, it means that the corresponding type of fault has occurred. You can then add code to handle each type of fault as needed.

The `PRECISERR` bit being set in the Bus Fault Status Register (part of the CFSR) indicates a precise data bus error. A precise data bus error occurs when the processor tries to access data at an address that is not allowed. 

This error is "precise" because the processor can tell exactly which instruction caused the error. The address of this instruction is stored in the `BFAR` (Bus Fault Address Register).

To find out which instruction caused the error, you can modify your HardFault handler to print out the value of the `BFAR`:

```c
#include "core_cm4.h" // Include CMSIS header for Cortex-M4

void HardFault_Handler(void)
{
    // Read the CFSR
    uint32_t cfsr = SCB->CFSR;

    // Check for bus fault
    if ((cfsr & SCB_CFSR_BUSFAULTSR_Msk) != 0) {
        // If PRECISERR is set
        if ((cfsr & SCB_CFSR_PRECISERR_Msk) != 0) {
            // Print the value of the BFAR
            printf("BFAR = %p\n", SCB->BFAR);
        }
    }

    while(1);
}
```

This will print out the address of the instruction that caused the precise data bus error. You can then use this address to find the offending instruction in your code.

